# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: netlify-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:netlify-platform/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:netlify-platform/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:netlify-platform/jamstack] In JAMstack websites, the application logic typically resides on the client side (for example, an embedded e-commerce checkout service that interacts with pre-rendered static content), without being tightly coupled to a backend server.
[src:netlify-platform/jamstack] JAMstack sites are usually served with a Git-based or headless CMS.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] The company enables building, deploying, and scaling websites whose source files are stored in the version control system Git and then generated into static web content files served via a content delivery network.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify functions are used in building dynamic websites with interactive features.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] The Netlify platform integrates with various plugins and application programming interfaces (APIs) to add extra features/functionality for web projects.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] The company was founded in 2014 by Danish entrepreneur Mathias Biilmann who noticed the emergence of Git-centered workflows with modern build tools and static site generators, while running Webpop, a content management startup based in San Francisco.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] In 2015, Biilmann invited Christian Bach, his childhood friend who was working as an executive at a creative services agency in Denmark, to join him as co-founder in his new venture.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] In 2017, MakerLoop was rebranded as Netlify.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Beyond the initial focus on hosting for static websites, the company expanded to a broader offering including serverless functions and test and deployment services.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On May 19, 2021, Netlify announced the acquisition of FeaturePeek, a Y Combinator and Matrix Partners backed startup that enables developer teams to preview frontend content.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On November 17, 2021, Netlify acquired Y Combinator and SignalFire-backed OneGraph to allow for the composition of apps with APIs and services using GraphQL.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On February 1, 2022, Netlify announced the acquisition of Quirrel, an open-source solution and service for managing and scheduling the execution of serverless functions and jobs.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] In February 2023, Netlify announced the acquisition of competitor company and Jamstack framework and platform provider Gatsby.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On June 29, 2023, Netlify announced the acquisition of Stackbit, a visual editing company run by entrepreneurs like Ryland King.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On August 16, 2016, Netlify raised $2.1 million from the founders of GitHub, Heroku, Rackspace Cloud, Bloomberg Beta and Tank Hill.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On August 9, 2017, the company announced that it had raised $12 million in series A funding from Andreessen Horowitz.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On October 9, 2018, the company issued a press release announcing that it had completed a series B round led by Kleiner Perkins—with participation from Andreessen Horowitz, Slack and Flickr co-founder Stewart Butterfield, Yelp CEO and co-founder Jeremy Stoppelman, among others—securing $30 million.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On March 4, 2020, Netlify secured $53 million in a series C round led by EQT Ventures, the venture capital branch of Swedish investment company EQT, with contributions by existing investors Andreessen Horowitz, Kleiner Perkins, and newcomer Preston-Werner Ventures.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] On November 17, 2021, Netlify secured $105 million in a series D round led by Bessemer Venture Partners at a $2 billion valuation, with contributions by existing investors Andreessen Horowitz, BOND, EQT Ventures, Kleiner Perkins, Mango Capital, and Menlo Ventures.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] This brought Netlify's total funding to $212 million.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify combines a platform for apps that streamlines the workflow for a development team.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify Build is a CI/CD infrastructure for frontend teams that is automated and pre-configured.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] It does not require a full-time administrator to manage the pipeline.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify Graph is a GraphQL-based approach to integrating distinct APIs to build a web app that strives to reduce the inherent complexities in mixing different data models, response formats, and authentication schemes; it is integrated with a number of APIs such as GitHub, Stripe, and Salesforce.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Developers write, test, and review code before production with Netlify CLI.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Within the CLI is Netlify Dev, which is a collection of development CLIs that brings the Netlify production environment down to a developer's local machine.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Deploy previews are used to view and leave feedback about a web project, with every annotation and comment synced to an organization's productivity tools.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify automatically builds a new Deploy Preview as a unique permanent URL for each Pull/Merge Request.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify Edge is a network used to power web experiences.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] It is fast due to its global distribution with automated prerendering.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] With Edge, apps are deployed to multiple cloud providers.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Worldwide caches are invalidated instantly as every global deployment is an atomic and instant update.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify's serverless capabilities include Netlify Functions, Background Functions, Scheduled Functions, and Edge Functions.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify Edge Functions allow developers to build fast web experiences by running dynamic content or an entire application from the network edge.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Edge Functions are built on open source runtime Deno to work with server-side features from existing web frameworks and edge-first frameworks.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Working as API endpoints deploy server-side code that automatically runs in response to events or completes jobs in the background by coding functions with JavaScript, TypeScript, or Go.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify executes functions written as full API endpoints, or functions can be executed directly from the frontend through JavaScript, or they can be called from other services through webhooks.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify works with open source contributors, web framework authors, digital agencies, and technology vendors in the modern web ecosystem; developers pick and plug in the tools for their projects.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify is an Enabler member of the MACH Alliance, group of independent technology companies that aim to advocate for open, best-of-breed technology ecosystems.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] JAMstack is a cloud-native web development architecture based on client-side JavaScript code, reusable APIs, and markup content.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] It was pioneered and created by Netlify.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] In its purest form, the idea of JAMstack is that a web application is pre-built into static pages, using content and code to generate the output.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] In basic terms, JAMstack is a significant shift in focus from the now abstractable back end to the now-powerful front end.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify is the host of the annual Jamstack Conf and runs the annual Jamstack Community Survey.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] In March 2017, Netlify CMS was named "GitHub project of the week" by the *Software Development Times*.
[src:netlify-platform/netlify] Netlify customers include Google, Facebook, Verizon, NBC, Samsung, Nike, Cisco, Atlassian, LiveChat, TriNet, Loblaw, Wieden+Kennedy, Vue.js, Citrix, Peloton, Kubernetes, Lodash, Smashing Magazine, Sequoia Capital, VMware, UW Health, Pan Macmillan, Victoria Beckham Beauty, Twilio, and Unilever.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:netlify-platform/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] A **static web page**, sometimes called a **flat page** or a **stationary page**, is a web page that is delivered to a web browser exactly as stored, in contrast to dynamic web pages which are generated by a web application.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] Consequently, a static web page displays the same information for all users, from all contexts, subject to modern capabilities of a web server to negotiate content-type or language of the document where such versions are available and the server is configured to do so.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] However, a webpage's JavaScript can introduce dynamic functionality which may make the static web page dynamic.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] Static web pages are often HTML documents, stored as files in the file system and made available by the web server over HTTP (nevertheless URLs ending with ".html" are not always static).
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] However, loose interpretations of the term could include web pages stored in a database, and could even include pages formatted using a template and served through an application server, as long as the page served is unchanging and presented essentially as stored.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] The content of static web pages remains stationary irrespective of the number of times it is viewed.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] Such web pages are suitable for the contents that rarely need to be updated, though modern web template systems are changing this.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] Maintaining large numbers of static pages as files can be impractical without automated tools, such as static site generators.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] Any personalization or interactivity has to run client-side, which is restricting.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] Cloud-based website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, offer no-code platforms for creating static and dynamic web pages through graphical interfaces, without requiring programming expertise.
[src:netlify-platform/static-web-page] Static site generators are applications that compile static websites - typically populating HTML templates in a predefined folder and file structure, with content supplied in a format such as Markdown or AsciiDoc.
